{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17630377","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17630377"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:15:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17313"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17313"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10003"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78218"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10003","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10003"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17313"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63627"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7689"},{"type":"tags","id":"10697"},{"type":"tags","id":"10732"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23438"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23528"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78218","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78218"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA scientist performs agarose gel electrophoresis to analyse PCR products. The gel is run at 100V for 60 minutes, with DNA samples loaded at the cathode (negative electrode).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the movement of DNA fragments during gel electrophoresis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Smaller fragments migrate faster toward the anode","Smaller fragments migrate faster toward the cathode","Smaller fragments remain stationary in the wells","Larger fragments migrate faster toward the anode","All fragments migrate at equal speeds"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring agarose gel electrophoresis, \u003Cstrong\u003Esmaller fragments migrate faster toward the anode\u003C/strong\u003E because DNA molecules must navigate through microscopic pores in the agarose gel matrix. The phosphate backbone of DNA carries a negative charge, causing migration toward the positive electrode (anode) when voltage is applied.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe rate of migration depends on:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EFragment size - smaller fragments encounter less resistance\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGel concentration - higher percentage gels have smaller pores\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EApplied voltage - higher voltage increases migration speed\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EDNA conformation - supercoiled DNA migrates differently than linear DNA\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmaller fragments migrate faster toward the cathode\u003C/strong\u003E - DNA\u0027s negative charge means it always migrates toward the positive electrode (anode)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmaller fragments remain stationary in the wells\u003C/strong\u003E - All DNA fragments will migrate when voltage is applied\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarger fragments migrate faster toward the anode\u003C/strong\u003E - Larger fragments experience more resistance from the gel matrix and move more slowly\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAll fragments migrate at equal speeds\u003C/strong\u003E - Migration speed varies inversely with fragment size\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis size-based separation allows researchers to determine fragment sizes by comparing their positions to a DNA ladder containing fragments of known lengths. The technique is essential for analysing PCR products, restriction digests, and other DNA samples.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Polymerase chain reaction (PCR) uses repeated cycles of denaturation, primer annealing, and extension to amplify specific DNA sequences.","DNA fragments can be separated by size using agarose gel electrophoresis, with smaller fragments moving faster through the gel.","The size of DNA fragments can be determined by comparing their migration distance to a DNA ladder of known fragment sizes."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Delidow BC, Lynch JP, Peluso JJ, White BA. Polymerase chain reaction : basic protocols. Methods Mol Biol. 1993;15:1-29. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21400259/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63627"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17313"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63627"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-09T21:22:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-09T21:25:56+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10003"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78218"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"